import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Read the data set
df = pd.read_csv('./data/radar.csv')

# Draw a radar graph
categories = list(df)[1:]
N = len(categories)

# What will be the angle of each axis in the plot? (we divide the plot / number of variable)
angles = [n / float(N) * 2 * np.pi for n in range(N)]
angles += angles[:1]

# Initialise the spider plot
ax = plt.subplot(111, polar=True)

# Draw one axe per variable + add labels labels yet
plt.xticks(angles[:-1], categories, color='grey', size=8)

# Draw ylabels
ax.set_rlabel_position(0)
plt.yticks([10,20,30], ["10","20","30"], color="grey", size=7)
plt.ylim(0,40)

# Plot data
ax.plot(angles, df['A'][1:], linewidth=1, linestyle='solid')
ax.fill(angles, df['A'][1:], 'b', alpha=0.1)

ax.plot(angles, df['B'][1:], linewidth=1, linestyle='solid')
ax.fill(angles, df['B'][1:], 'r', alpha=0.1)

# Add legend
plt.legend(labels=df['Name'][1:], loc=(0.9, .95), labelspacing=0.1, fontsize='small')

plt.savefig('./output/radar.png')
```

# Apply bitwise AND operation on original image and binary mask to get final result 
result_image = cv2.bitwise_and(image,image,mask=foreground_mask)

result_rgb_image = cv2.cvtColor(result_image,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

import jieba

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Load data from ./data/insurance.csv
data = pd.read_csv('./data/insurance.csv')

# Draw a scatter plot with age and bmi
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.scatter(data['age'], data['bmi'])
plt.xlabel('age')
plt.ylabel('bmi')

# Calculate the average insurance amount of different ages
age_group = data.groupby('age')['charges'].mean()

# Draw a line chart with the average insurance amount of different ages
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.plot(age_group.index, age_group.values)
plt.xlabel('age')
plt.ylabel('average insurance amount')

plt.savefig('./output/result.png')
print('./output/result.png')
```

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Load the data
data = pd.read_excel("./data/Farm_Weather_Data.xlsx")

# Preprocess the data
data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'])
data['Year'] = data['Date'].dt.year
data['Month'] = data['Date'].dt.month
data['Day'] = data['Date'].dt.day
data['Hour'] = data['Date'].dt.hour
data['Minute'] = data['Date'].dt.minute
data['Second'] = data['Date'].dt.second
data['Dayofweek'] = data['Date'].dt.dayofweek
data = data.drop(columns=['Date'])

# Train a model to predict the weather
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

X = data.drop(columns=['Temperature'])
y = data['Temperature']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
sc = StandardScaler()
X_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = sc.transform(X_test)
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Visualize the result
plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred)
plt.xlabel('Actual Temperature')
plt.ylabel('Predicted Temperature')
plt.title('Actual Temperature vs. Predicted Temperature')
plt.savefig('./output/result.png')
print('./output/result.png')

img = img*mask2[:,:,np.newaxis]

plt.show()
